@misc{noauthor_jic-01-2023-0003_proof_hipdf_nodate,
	title = {{JIC}-01-2023-0003\_Proof\_hi.pdf},
	abstract = {Review Comments:

This paper aims to examine the moderating role of digital transformation in the relationship between intellectual capital and innovation in the context of Chinese manufacturing firms. Using data of manufacturing firms in listed A-shares in Shenzhen stock exchange from year 2012 to 2021, they find that IC has an excellent level of engagement with innovation on average, and such relationship is positively moderated by DT. Moreover, among the elements of DT, the Big Data show the most significant moderate effect. Digital transformation is an interesting topic. My concerns of this paper are as follows.

（1） Research motivation.

In the introduction section, the authors have stated the importance of intellectual capital, innovation, and digital transformation, but why the moderating role of digital transformation between intellectual capital and innovation should be studied is not well clarified.  Are there any conflicting findings for the relationship between IC and innovation so that we need to uncover under what conditions would IC exert the most powerful influence on innovation? Although the authors have provided the following reason on Page 3, “While there have been a few researchers examining the relationship between IC and innovation in China (e.g., Xu and Li 2019; Wu et al. 2020; Xu and Li, 2022), little attention is given to investigate the role of DT on the IC and innovation”, I don not think such arguments would be enough. The facts that this topic is under limited study does not necessarily justify that this subject is worth studying.

(2) Research contribution.

The authors have listed three aspects of contributions regarding this study on Page 4, some of them I do not agree.

“First, there is presently no available practical understanding of how DT moderates the relationship between IC and innovation. We contribute to the literature by examining the moderating role of DT on the IC and innovation.” To study a subject that has never been studied does not qualify to be a contribution.

“Third, regarding the contribution of methodology, we have performed the bibliometric analysis for the literature review and adopted python to extract the DT data from annual reports for the content analysis. The Partial Least Square-Structural Equation Modeling (PLS-SEM) is established and the smart PLS 3.0 software used to analyze the data.” Performing bibliometric analysis for the literature review, applying python to extract data from annual reports, and employing PLS-SEM technique can hardly be granted as a contribution, as they are just the operational procedures to obtain the research outputs. Moreover, such techniques are widely applied in the current research.

(3) Literature review.

While I read the literature review section, I expect to know the research advancement and findings that are related to this topic. Unfortunately, I just get a bunch of numbers, such as the co-authorship network of the countries, co-occurrence of keywords, and citation of the sources and authors. I admit that these figures are import to understand the research trends to this topic, but they could not help me to understand what findings have been uncovered, and what kind of problems are still under limited study. More importantly, I could get the connections between this literature review section and the following sections such as hypotheses development and Discussion.

(4) Hypotheses development

The relationship between arguments and hypotheses are very weak. For instance, on Page 14, the authors propose that “H1: IC is positively associated with innovation.” ()“JIC-01-2023-0003\_Proof\_hi.pdf”, p. 14(), but based on the argument on Page 13-14, I can hardly get such hypothesis. Some paragraphs talk about competitive advantage and capabilities, but why intellectual capital would be associated with innovation is not well documented. The authors stated that, “Analyses linking IC to innovation such as Buenechea-Elberdin et al. (2018), Duodu and Rowlinson (2019), Berraies (2019), which have been discussed in the literature review, support that the IC directly or indirectly positively affect the innovation.” ()“JIC-01-2023-0003\_Proof\_hi.pdf”, p. 14(), then why do you bother to study this topic again?},
